1
00:00:00,500 --> 00:00:08,176
Historical specimen records look quiet, but one bad reconciliation can corrupt biodiversity data for years.

2
00:00:08,176 --> 00:00:13,806
Specimen Casebook is an auditable evidence-reconciliation workspace for natural history collections.

3
00:00:13,806 --> 00:00:16,876
One rule: conflict preserved, science protected.

4
00:00:17,876 --> 00:00:22,123
A specimen label and a field ledger both say 1907.

5
00:00:22,123 --> 00:00:24,247
A legacy database says 1909.

6
00:00:24,247 --> 00:00:28,919
Copy that forward, and a transcription error becomes a published fact.

7
00:00:28,919 --> 00:00:32,317
The problem is not that digitization is slow.

8
00:00:32,317 --> 00:00:35,290
It is that uncertainty disappears during digitization.

9
00:00:36,290 --> 00:00:39,711
Our user is a herbarium collections data manager.

10
00:00:39,711 --> 00:00:46,981
They reconcile labels, ledgers, legacy rows, and notebooks by hand, and the reasoning is rarely written down.

11
00:00:46,981 --> 00:00:53,396
Their need: reconcile each field, preserve every disagreement, and show where every value came from.

12
00:00:54,396 --> 00:00:56,483
Here is the working system.

13
00:00:56,483 --> 00:01:02,742
Claude reads each source, extracts field-level claims with citations, and compares them field by field.

14
00:01:02,742 --> 00:01:10,671
The summary separates confirmed values from inferred, conflicting, and missing evidence — and exports Darwin Core without losing provenance.

15
00:01:11,671 --> 00:01:13,966
This is the core demo.

16
00:01:13,966 --> 00:01:16,720
The label says June 17, 1907.

17
00:01:16,720 --> 00:01:19,475
The ledger says June 19, 1907.

18
00:01:19,475 --> 00:01:22,688
The legacy database says June 17, 1909.

19
00:01:22,688 --> 00:01:26,819
Specimen Casebook does not pick the most convenient answer.

20
00:01:26,819 --> 00:01:36,918
It marks the collection date CONFLICTING, keeps all three claims attached to their sources, and recommends: do not publish without human review.

21
00:01:36,918 --> 00:01:40,131
Without this, 1909 could ship as fact.

22
00:01:41,131 --> 00:01:44,283
The architecture separates language-model reasoning from publication policy.

23
00:01:44,283 --> 00:01:51,770
Claude Opus 4.8 returns every claim under a strict JSON schema, carrying a verbatim quote and a source id.

24
00:01:51,770 --> 00:02:01,621
A deterministic layer then re-checks each quote as an exact substring, drops anything invented, and refuses to auto-resolve a field when two grounded values disagree.

25
00:02:01,621 --> 00:02:07,532
I built that safety layer, and the adversarial tests that prove it, in Claude Code.

26
00:02:07,532 --> 00:02:11,079
Claude proposes; the policy layer decides what can ship.

27
00:02:12,079 --> 00:02:14,756
We measure restraint, not just extraction.

28
00:02:14,756 --> 00:02:21,005
Our key metric is unsupported resolution rate: conflicts collapsed into one answer without evidence.

29
00:02:21,005 --> 00:02:25,022
It measures 0%, across adversarial tests and live runs.

30
00:02:25,022 --> 00:02:27,700
Not a target — a result.

31
00:02:28,700 --> 00:02:35,309
Specimen Casebook turns scattered historical evidence into trustworthy biodiversity records, without silent certainty.

32
00:02:35,309 --> 00:02:41,410
It is working software for the collections data managers science depends on.

33
00:02:41,410 --> 00:02:42,427
Conflict preserved.

34
00:02:42,427 --> 00:02:43,444
Science protected.
